      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":55,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a fully conversational effort — you should be able to speak in full sentences. Stay in the 5:04–5:34/km range and let your body absorb last week's training load.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with 5 minutes of easy walking or very light jogging to ease into the effort.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of walking and light dynamic stretching — hip circles, calf raises, leg swings.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This run is pure aerobic base work. After a solid 60 km week, your body needs blood flow and recovery stimulus without additional stress. Resist the urge to push — the easy days are where adaptation actually happens.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":57,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":252,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy at 5:04–5:34/km. Include 4 x 20-second strides in the final minute to prime your legs.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":252,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":3,\"notes\":\"3 x 10 minutes at threshold pace (4:12/km) with 90-second easy jog recovery between each. This is comfortably hard — controlled, not labored. You should be able to say a few words but not hold a conversation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"3 km easy cool-down at 5:04–5:34/km. Let your breathing fully settle before stopping.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"3 km easy jog, finishing with 4 short strides of 20 seconds each to activate your fast-twitch fibers before the threshold work.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"3 km easy jog followed by 5 minutes of static stretching — focus on calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold work is the cornerstone of marathon fitness. Running at lactate threshold teaches your body to clear lactate more efficiently, which directly translates to holding marathon pace for 42 km. The cruise interval format (work-rest-work) lets you accumulate more quality time at threshold than a single continuous tempo run would. Three reps of 10 minutes is a meaningful stimulus without being excessive at this stage of your build.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":334,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Keep this genuinely easy — 5:20–5:34/km is perfectly appropriate here. This is a recovery run the day before your long run, so the goal is to stay loose and arrive at Sunday feeling fresh.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 3-minute walk before easing into your easy jog.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"End with a 5-minute walk and light stretching. Prioritize sleep and hydration tonight.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This short Saturday run keeps your legs moving without creating fatigue ahead of Sunday's long run. Think of it as priming the pump — a little blood flow, a little rhythm, nothing more. If you feel flat or tired, it is completely fine to shorten this to 6 km or skip it in favor of extra rest.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run with Marathon Pace Finish\",\"target_distance_km\":26,\"target_duration_minutes\":140,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":334,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":268,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 3 km easy at 5:20–5:34/km. Let your body warm up fully before settling into your long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":100,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Km 3–21 at easy long run pace (5:04–5:34/km). Stay aerobic, stay relaxed. Practice your fueling strategy — aim for a gel or equivalent carbohydrate every 40–45 minutes.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":268,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 4 km at marathon goal pace (4:28/km). This is the key stimulus — running at goal pace on tired legs teaches your body what race day will feel like. Stay controlled and focused.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":7,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":334,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk or very easy jog for the final few minutes. Begin your recovery routine immediately after finishing.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start easy and resist the temptation to run faster than 5:20/km in the first 5 km. Your long run pace should feel almost too easy at the start.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"After finishing, walk for 5 minutes, then do 10 minutes of gentle stretching. Prioritize protein and carbohydrate intake within 30–45 minutes of finishing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is the most important run of your week. The long run builds the aerobic engine, mitochondrial density, and fat oxidation capacity that marathon racing demands. The marathon-pace finish in the final 4 km is a deliberate training tool — it teaches your neuromuscular system to hold goal pace under fatigue, which is exactly what the last 10 km of your race will require. At 26 km, you are maintaining your current long run distance while adding quality at the end. This is a meaningful but manageable stimulus.\",\"perceived_effort\":7}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
